---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import BmiCalculator from '../components/BmiCalculator.astro';
import FaqSection from '../components/FaqSection.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="BMI Calculator for Women — Female Body Mass Index Guide"
  description="Free BMI calculator for women. Understand healthy BMI ranges for adult females, how hormones and body composition affect BMI interpretation, and what a normal BMI means for women."
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl px-4 py-10 sm:px-6">

    <section class="mb-10 max-w-3xl">
      <p class="text-sm font-medium uppercase tracking-wider text-(--color-accent-deep)">
        For Women
      </p>
      <h1 class="font-display mt-2 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-(--color-ink) sm:text-5xl">
        BMI Calculator for Women
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-relaxed text-(--color-body)">
        Calculate your body mass index instantly. The formula is the same for all adults — but understanding
        what your number means as a woman requires a bit more context.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[1.15fr_0.85fr] lg:gap-12">
      <BmiCalculator />

      <aside class="space-y-6 text-sm leading-relaxed text-(--color-body) lg:sticky lg:top-24 lg:self-start">

        <div class="rounded-xl border border-(--color-hairline) bg-(--color-accent)/5 p-5">
          <h2 class="font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">BMI ranges for women (adults)</h2>
          <table class="mt-3 w-full text-left text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-(--color-hairline) text-(--color-mute)">
                <th class="py-2 pr-2">Category</th>
                <th class="py-2">BMI (kg/m²)</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="border-b border-(--color-hairline)/60"><td class="py-2">Underweight</td><td>&lt; 18.5</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-(--color-hairline)/60"><td class="py-2">Normal</td><td>18.5 – 24.9</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-(--color-hairline)/60"><td class="py-2">Overweight</td><td>25 – 29.9</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="py-2">Obese</td><td>≥ 30</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
          <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-(--color-mute)">Source: WHO. Thresholds are the same for women and men.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-xl border border-(--color-hairline) bg-(--color-canvas) p-5 space-y-2">
          <h2 class="font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">Average BMI for women by age (US)</h2>
          <table class="mt-2 w-full text-left text-xs">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-(--color-hairline) text-(--color-mute)">
                <th class="py-1.5 pr-2">Age group</th>
                <th class="py-1.5">Avg BMI</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="border-b border-(--color-hairline)/60"><td class="py-1.5">20–39</td><td>26.8</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-(--color-hairline)/60"><td class="py-1.5">40–59</td><td>28.7</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="py-1.5">60+</td><td>28.2</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
          <p class="text-xs text-(--color-mute)">Source: CDC NHANES data. Average ≠ healthy — use it only for context.</p>
        </div>

        <p>
          <strong class="text-(--color-ink)">Medical disclaimer:</strong> This tool is not a substitute for
          professional medical advice, diagnosis, or treatment. BMI is a screening measure and does not
          measure body fat directly.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </div>

    <article class="prose-section mx-auto mt-16 max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-(--color-body)">

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">
          What is a healthy BMI for women?
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          The WHO defines a healthy BMI range as <strong>18.5 to 24.9 kg/m²</strong> for all adults, regardless
          of sex. However, women naturally have a higher body-fat percentage than men at the same BMI — typically
          6–11 percentage points more — due to hormonal differences, breast tissue, and reproductive organs.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          This means two women with the same BMI of 22 can have meaningfully different body compositions depending
          on their age, fitness level, and genetics. BMI is best used as a starting point rather than a
          definitive health score.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">
          How hormones affect BMI interpretation
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Oestrogen promotes fat storage in the hips, thighs, and breasts. This distribution (called
          gynoid or pear-shaped fat) is generally less metabolically harmful than abdominal (android or
          apple-shaped) fat. After menopause, oestrogen levels drop and fat often redistributes toward
          the abdomen, raising cardiovascular and metabolic risk — even with no change in BMI.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) and thyroid disorders can also affect weight independently of
          diet and exercise, making BMI less reliable as a solo metric.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">
          BMI and pregnancy
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          BMI is <strong>not used during pregnancy</strong>. Weight gain is expected and healthy — typically
          11–16 kg for women with a normal pre-pregnancy BMI. Your pre-pregnancy BMI helps doctors set
          personalised weight-gain targets, but your obstetrician will track progress using dedicated
          pregnancy charts, not standard BMI thresholds.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">
          Limitations of BMI for women
        </h2>
        <ul class="mt-3 list-disc pl-5 space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Muscle mass:</strong> Women who strength-train may have higher BMI despite healthy body fat.</li>
          <li><strong>Menopause:</strong> Fat redistribution raises health risk without necessarily changing BMI.</li>
          <li><strong>Ethnicity:</strong> Asian women may face elevated metabolic risk at BMI levels below 25.</li>
          <li><strong>Bone density:</strong> Denser bones weigh more — BMI doesn't distinguish bone from fat.</li>
          <li><strong>Age:</strong> Body composition changes with age; a BMI of 22 at 25 differs from 22 at 65.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">
          Better alternatives for women
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Clinicians often pair BMI with:
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-2 list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
          <li><strong>Waist circumference</strong> — risk increases above 80 cm (31.5 in) for women</li>
          <li><strong>Waist-to-height ratio</strong> — keep below 0.5 for most adults</li>
          <li><strong>Body fat percentage</strong> — measured via DEXA scan, bioelectrical impedance, or skinfold calipers</li>
          <li><strong>Blood markers</strong> — cholesterol, blood glucose, blood pressure alongside weight</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

    </article>

    <div class="mx-auto mt-16 max-w-3xl">
      <p class="mb-6 text-sm text-(--color-body)">
        <a href="/" class="text-(--color-link) hover:underline">← Main BMI calculator</a>
        &nbsp;·&nbsp;
        <a href="/bmi-calculator-for-men" class="text-(--color-link) hover:underline">BMI for men →</a>
      </p>
    </div>

  </div>
</BaseLayout>